<div id="review_4110718033" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4110718033" />
    <a title="Juan Valencia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/134043614-juan-valencia"><img alt="Juan Valencia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624003685p2/134043614.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4110718033?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Juan Valencia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Juan Valencia" href="/user/show/134043614-juan-valencia">Juan Valencia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4110718033" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11317651800079826507">4.5 ⭐️<br/><br/>I have read a lot of “misery lit” recently, and thus maybe I’ve gone into this narrative in such an exhausted shape that I couldn’t help but feel overwhelmed AND underwhelmed at the ferocity of its details, and was unable to connect at times with the truly monstrous world that unfolds.<br/><br/>However, what really saved and elevated this narrative for me was the style, the deep plunge into a murky and tortured psychology that McCabe undertakes unflinchingly. Francie’s descent into deviancy is belie</span>
  <span id="freeText11317651800079826507" style="display:none">4.5 ⭐️<br /><br />I have read a lot of “misery lit” recently, and thus maybe I’ve gone into this narrative in such an exhausted shape that I couldn’t help but feel overwhelmed AND underwhelmed at the ferocity of its details, and was unable to connect at times with the truly monstrous world that unfolds.<br /><br />However, what really saved and elevated this narrative for me was the style, the deep plunge into a murky and tortured psychology that McCabe undertakes unflinchingly. Francie’s descent into deviancy is believable, as infuriating as it is pitiable as it is even laughable at times. There’s a true grasp on details and tone that makes the interiority real, gripping, and leaves you a feeling of unease at having been gripped by such a grimy, indelicate grasp. <br /><br />And then there’s the ending: One of the most brutal and disturbing things I’ve read in a long while, told with such bluntness, even a peaceful quietness that’s truly unshakable.<br /><br />This is one of the greats, even with its flaws in content, which may well be personal psychological factors for me. Truly recommended for explorers of the disturbing, grotesque, and poignant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11317651800079826507" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


