    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_28156388" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/28156388" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/787522-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1210278686p2/787522.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/28156388?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/787522-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780880641470" href="/book/show/138969.The_Butcher_Boy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/787522-paul?shelf=2008">2008</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28156388" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12963351840000586084">Absolutely phenomenal. This is a must-read for anyone with a heart who can stand a bit of the old ultraviolence. It would be terribly reductive to describe this novel as a mashup of <i>The Catcher in the Rye</i> and <i>A Clockwork Orange</i>, so I won&apos;t describe it as such, but its narrator definitely has that Holdenesque naivete and charm to him, and the language, while not as inventive as Burgess&apos;, is still a lot of fun. I kept telling people about the book as I was reading it and my descriptions all sounde</span>
  <span id="freeText12963351840000586084" style="display:none">Absolutely phenomenal. This is a must-read for anyone with a heart who can stand a bit of the old ultraviolence. It would be terribly reductive to describe this novel as a mashup of <i>The Catcher in the Rye</i> and <i>A Clockwork Orange</i>, so I won't describe it as such, but its narrator definitely has that Holdenesque naivete and charm to him, and the language, while not as inventive as Burgess', is still a lot of fun. I kept telling people about the book as I was reading it and my descriptions all sounded incredibly sad. It's not a sad book, though, per se. Francie Brady has quite a sad lot dealt to him, sure, quite an unfortunate lot, but how he deals with it -- through a transparent, young-boy toughness and escapist imagination (McCabe uses this technique brilliantly, never as an escape mechanism himself; it's subtle and always appropriate) -- is where the book's humor and real pathos come from. Francie has this wonderful habit of saying what he wishes he could say and then immediately saying "No I didn't say that I said . . . " McCabe uses punctuation sparingly, and the book has a bit of a stream of consciousness feel to it, though it's completely accessible and an easy read. Still, at about 200 pages, it hardly feels short. Just incredibly well-crafted. Francie is funny as hell, but you wonder whether you'd consider him an absolute psychopath were his actions not filtered through his own voice/eyes. What a great, complex, and engaging character. His relationship to his friend Joe later on the novel is absolutely heartbreaking and true to life. A few small moments of literary transcendence here. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12963351840000586084" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

