<div id="review_1139624894" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1139624894" />
    <a title="gaudeo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2428663-gaudeo"><img alt="gaudeo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1330366484p2/2428663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1139624894?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="gaudeo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="gaudeo" href="/user/show/2428663-gaudeo">gaudeo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1139624894" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13337463122406506430">This book, a Booker Prize nominee, is disturbing but very enlightening. Set in Ireland, it follows the adolescence of Francis &quot;Francie&quot; Brady, the son of an alcoholic father and a mother literally at her wits&apos; end. The family is poor, and I think the book&apos;s biggest strength is showing how poverty traps people from one generation to the next. But one cannot overlook Francie&apos;s main problem: he gets in trouble, and progressively more trouble as the story develops. McCabe does a great job of depicti</span>
  <span id="freeText13337463122406506430" style="display:none">This book, a Booker Prize nominee, is disturbing but very enlightening. Set in Ireland, it follows the adolescence of Francis "Francie" Brady, the son of an alcoholic father and a mother literally at her wits' end. The family is poor, and I think the book's biggest strength is showing how poverty traps people from one generation to the next. But one cannot overlook Francie's main problem: he gets in trouble, and progressively more trouble as the story develops. McCabe does a great job of depicting how people fear Francie, and how he toys with their fears. I won't reveal what happens, but it is unforgettable. This is a thought-provoking, haunting book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13337463122406506430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


